name: 4-benzoylbutyric acid

Adding the benzoyl group (Ph-C(=O)-) will significantly raise the melting point due to the increase in molecular complexity, planarity, and capacity for intermolecular interactions, such as dipole-dipole attraction and possible pi-stacking with neighboring aromatic rings. This effect can add upwards of 70 degrees Celsius. The carboxylic acid group (-COOH) at the end of the butyric chain will further increase the melting point due to the possibility of strong hydrogen bonding and increased polarity, which could add an additional 40 to 50 degrees Celsius. The butyric acid chain itself also contributes, given that linear alkyl chains can raise the melting point by incrementally increasing the London dispersion forces; each methylene group (CH2) in a chain can be estimated to add about 5 degrees Celsius with the 4 carbons in the butyric acid adding about 20 degrees in total. Syncing these effects leads to the prediction below:
Prediction: 5.5 (base for benzene) + 70 (benzoyl group) + 50 (carboxylic acid group) + 20 (butyric chain) = 145.5
